# Security Review: `app.js`

## Scope

The file is a 23-line Express application exposing two endpoints (`GET /health`, `GET /users`). The attack surface is small, but several real issues exist and more will become critical as soon as the app grows. I've organized findings by severity.

---

## HIGH Severity

### H1. Sensitive data exposed without authentication (OWASP A01 – Broken Access Control, A02 – Cryptographic Failures / Data Exposure)

`GET /users` returns user records including email addresses to anyone who can reach the server. There is no authentication, no authorization, and no rate limiting.

```js
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    ...
  ]);
});
```

**Fix** — Require authentication and return only fields the caller is authorized to see:

```js
const requireAuth = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, '');
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, { algorithms: ['HS256'] });
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  }
};

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Only return PII to admins; regular users get a redacted view
  const isAdmin = req.user.roles?.includes('admin');
  res.json(users.map(u => isAdmin ? u : { id: u.id, name: u.name }));
});
```

### H2. No security headers (OWASP A05 – Security Misconfiguration)

Without `helmet`, the response lacks `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `Content-Security-Policy`, `X-Frame-Options`, etc. Express also sets `X-Powered-By: Express` by default, which advertises the stack.

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
```

### H3. Secrets / configuration hardcoded

The port `3000` is hardcoded. More importantly, there is no mechanism for loading secrets safely, and the presence of a `.env.test` alongside the app suggests env files may be committed. Any credentials, JWT secrets, or DB URIs MUST come from `process.env`, and `.env*` files should be in `.gitignore` (with `.env.example` as the only committed template).

```js
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`listening on ${PORT}`));
```

---

## MEDIUM Severity

### M1. No rate limiting / DoS protection (OWASP A04 – Insecure Design)

Any client can hammer either endpoint. Add `express-rate-limit`, and consider a tighter limiter on auth endpoints when they're added:

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100, standardHeaders: true, legacyHeaders: false }));
```

### M2. No CORS policy defined

By default, same-origin browsers will be fine, but once a front-end is introduced someone will reach for `app.use(cors())` with no options, which reflects any origin. Define an allow-list explicitly now:

```js
const cors = require('cors');
const allowed = (process.env.CORS_ORIGINS || '').split(',').filter(Boolean);
app.use(cors({ origin: (o, cb) => cb(null, !o || allowed.includes(o)), credentials: true }));
```

### M3. No body-size limits (OWASP A04)

When `express.json()` or `express.urlencoded()` is added later, the default 100 kB limit may be exceeded by design or an attacker may try very large payloads. Set it explicitly:

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

### M4. No global error handler — stack traces may leak (OWASP A09 / A05)

Any thrown error in a future handler will fall through to Express's default handler, which in non-production mode renders a stack trace. Add a terminal error handler that logs internally but returns a generic response:

```js
// 404
app.use((req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: 'not found' }));

// error handler (must have 4 args)
app.use((err, req, res, _next) => {
  req.log?.error({ err }, 'unhandled error'); // structured logger, not console
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'internal error' });
});
```

### M5. `app.listen()` runs on `require()`

`module.exports = app` is after `app.listen(3000, ...)`, so any test or tool that `require`s this file immediately binds port 3000. Aside from breaking tests, it means importing the module has a side effect — and if the module is required twice (e.g. via a watcher), you'll get `EADDRINUSE`. Split the server bootstrap from the app definition:

```js
// app.js
module.exports = app;

// server.js
const app = require('./app');
app.listen(process.env.PORT || 3000);
```

---

## LOW Severity / Hygiene

### L1. No HTTPS enforcement

In production, terminate TLS at a proxy and redirect HTTP → HTTPS, or set HSTS via helmet's default. Do not rely on the Node process to serve plain HTTP publicly.

### L2. No request logging / audit trail (OWASP A09 – Logging & Monitoring Failures)

`console.log` of "Server running" is the only log line. Add a structured logger (pino, winston) with request IDs so security events are traceable:

```js
const pino = require('pino-http')();
app.use(pino);
```

### L3. No graceful shutdown

On SIGTERM (e.g., container stop) in-flight requests are killed. Capture the server handle and close it cleanly:

```js
const server = app.listen(PORT);
for (const sig of ['SIGINT', 'SIGTERM']) {
  process.on(sig, () => server.close(() => process.exit(0)));
}
```

### L4. `/health` leaks server time

`new Date().toISOString()` is harmless on its own but becomes a timing oracle fingerprint when combined with other info. Prefer returning just `{ status: 'ok' }` on a public liveness probe, and put detailed diagnostics on an internal-only `/internal/health` route.

